= [2,1,4]\nOutput: -1\nExplanation: It's impossible to sort the array using right shifts.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= nums.length <= 100\n1 <= nums[i] <= 100\nnums contains distinct integers.\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def minimumRightShifts(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def minimumRightShifts(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        n = len(nums)\n        i = 1\n        while i < n and nums[i - 1] < nums[i]:\n            i += 1\n        if i == n:\n            return 0  # The array is already sorted\n        if i < n - 1 and nums[-1] > nums[0]:\n            return -1  # More than one place where the order is broken, or the last element is greater than the first\n        \n        k = i + 1\n        while k < n and nums[k - 1] < nums[k]:\n            k += 1\n        \n        return -1 if k < n else n - i\n```\n\nThis code checks the conditions for the array to be sortable by a certain number of right shifts. It first finds the point where the order breaks, then checks if the rest of the array is sorted and if the last element can be placed at the beginning to form a sorted array. If these conditions are met, it returns the number of shifts required; otherwise, it returns -1.", "estimated_date": 1694304000000}